In [81]:
X_NBA_Original = NBA.drop(["Rk", "Pk", "Draft Year", "Team", "Player Name", "College", "Year", "WS", "WS/48", "VORP", "BPM"], axis=1)

# We have droped "VORP" from the data set because the "BPM" is used to calculate VORP. If I use the feature "VORP", our model will mainly calculate 
# BPM from VORP, because of which we will not understand the proper importance of other features in predicting BPM.

# Set up the plot grid
num_columns = X_NBA_ONE.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns  # Only numeric features
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))

for i, column in enumerate(num_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(6, 6, i)  # Adjust 6x6 grid based on the number of features
    sns.histplot(X_NBA_ONE[column], kde=True, bins=30, edgecolor='black')
    plt.title(f'Histogram for {column}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Creating a baseline model with mean and median for the regression tasks¶

In [102]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
In [103]:
# Predicting the mean BPM as the baseline
baseline_prediction_mean = np.mean(y_NBA_ONE_train)
In [104]:
# Apply baseline prediction (mean) to the test set
y_pred_baseline_mean = [baseline_prediction_mean] * len(y_NBA_ONE_test)
In [105]:
# Evaluate the baseline model using mean squared error and R-squared
mse_baseline_mean = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_baseline_mean)
r2_baseline_mean = r2_score(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_baseline_mean)
In [106]:
print(f"Baseline Model (Mean):\n Mean Squared Error: {mse_baseline_mean}\n R-squared: {r2_baseline_mean}\n")

Baseline Model (Mean):
 Mean Squared Error: 13.02904968828328
 R-squared: -0.007364885998565329
In [107]:
#Predicting the median BPM as the baseline
baseline_prediction_median = np.median(y_NBA_ONE_train)
In [108]:
# Apply baseline prediction (median) to the test set
y_pred_baseline_median = [baseline_prediction_median] * len(y_NBA_ONE_test)
In [109]:
mse_baseline_median = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_baseline_median)
r2_baseline_median = r2_score(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_baseline_median)
In [110]:
print(f"Baseline Model (Median):\n Mean Squared Error: {mse_baseline_median}\n R-squared: {r2_baseline_median}\n")

Random Forest Regressor for just only nba draft data¶

In [111]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
In [112]:
# Initializing the random forest regressor with 100 trees
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
In [113]:
# Fitting the model on training data
rf.fit(X_NBA_ONE_train, y_NBA_ONE_train)

In [116]:
# Hyperparameter Tuning for the Random Forest Regressor Model
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [117]:
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [10, 20, 30],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10]
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_NBA_ONE_train, y_NBA_ONE_train)

print(grid_search.best_params_)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
In [2510]:

In [2511]:

# Scale the test data

In [2512]:
# Initialize the XGBoost regressor
xgb_model_nba = xgb.XGBRegressor(
    n_estimators=100,  # Number of boosting rounds (trees)
    learning_rate=0.1, # Shrinkage rate
    max_depth=3,       # Maximum depth of trees
    subsample=0.8,     # Fraction of samples used for fitting individual base learners
    random_state=42
)

In [2517]:
# Hyperparameter Tuning

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'subsample': [0.8, 1.0]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV with XGBRegressor
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=xgb.XGBRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='r2')

# Fit the grid search to the scaled training data
grid_search.fit(X_train_scaled_nba_boost, y_NBA_ONE_train)

# Print the best parameters
print(f'Best parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}')

Best parameters: {'learning_rate': 0.2, 'max_depth': 3, 'n_estimators': 100, 'subsample': 0.8}
In [2518]:
# Use the best model for prediction
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_best = best_model.predict(X_test_scaled_nba_boost)
In [2519]:
# Evaluate the best model
mse_best = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_best)
r2_best = r2_score(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_best)

print(f'Best Mean Squared Error: {mse_best}')
print(f'Best R-squared: {r2_best}')

Best Mean Squared Error: 2.9560101170515907
Best R-squared: 0.7714506532850105

Artificial Neural Network (ANN) for NBA Draft Data¶

In [2521]:
# Split NBA draft data set names: X_NBA_ONE_train, X_NBA_ONE_test, y_NBA_ONE_train, y_NBA_ONE_test
In [2522]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2523]:
# Initialize the standard scaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
In [2524]:
# Scale the training data
X_train_scaled_nba_ann = scaler.fit_transform(X_NBA_ONE_train)

# Scale the test data
X_test_scaled_nba_ann = scaler.transform(X_NBA_ONE_test)
In [2525]:
# Initialize the model
model_nba_ann = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_nba_ann.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train_scaled_nba_ann.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_nba_ann.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_nba_ann.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_nba_ann.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_nba_ann.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2526]:
# Train the model
history = model_nba_ann.fit(X_train_scaled_nba_ann, y_NBA_ONE_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

In [2530]:
# We further use L2 Regularization to see whether we can make this model even a better model or not.

from keras.regularizers import l2

# Define the neural network architecture with L2 regularization
model_nba_ann_l2 = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_nba_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train_scaled_nba_ann.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.01

# Additional hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_nba_ann_l2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
model_nba_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))

# Output layer with 1 neuron (for regression)
model_nba_ann_l2.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model
model_nba_ann_l2.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])

Deep Neural Network (DNN) for NBA data¶

In [2535]:
# Split NBA draft data set names: X_NBA_ONE_train, X_NBA_ONE_test, y_NBA_ONE_train, y_NBA_ONE_test
In [2536]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2537]:
# Initialize the standard scaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Scale the training data
X_train_scaled_nba_dnn = scaler.fit_transform(X_NBA_ONE_train)

# Scale the test data
X_test_scaled_nba_dnn = scaler.transform(X_NBA_ONE_test)
In [2538]:
# Initialize the model
model_nba_dnn = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_nba_dnn.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train_scaled_nba_dnn.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_nba_dnn.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_nba_dnn.add(Dropout(0.3))  # Dropout layer to prevent overfitting
model_nba_dnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_nba_dnn.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_nba_dnn.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2539]:
# Train the model
history = model_nba_dnn.fit(X_train_scaled_nba_dnn, y_NBA_ONE_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

model_nba_dnn_l2 = models.Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_nba_dnn_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train_scaled_nba_dnn.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.001

# Hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_nba_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_nba_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_nba_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))

# Output layer for regression (for predicting BPM)
model_nba_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(1))  # Single output for regression

# Compile the model
model_nba_dnn_l2.compile(optimizer='adam', 
              loss='mean_squared_error',  # For regression
              metrics=['mae'])  # Mean Absolute Error as an additional metric
In [2544]:
# Train the model
history_l2 = model_nba_dnn_l2.fit(X_train_scaled_nba_dnn, y_NBA_ONE_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

In [2553]:
# Hyperparameter Tuning
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 10, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

# Fit the grid search
grid_search.fit(X_train_scaled_nba_dtr, y_NBA_ONE_train)

# Best parameters
print(f"Best Parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}")

# Use the best model
best_model_nba_dtr_tune = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predict using the best model
y_pred_best_nba_dtr_tune = best_model_nba_dtr_tune.predict(X_test_scaled_nba_dtr)

# Evaluate the best model
mse_best_nba_dtr_tune = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_best_nba_dtr_tune)
r2_best_nba_dtr_tune = r2_score(y_NBA_ONE_test, y_pred_best_nba_dtr_tune)

print(f"Best Mean Squared Error: {mse_best_nba_dtr_tune}")
print(f"Best R-squared: {r2_best_nba_dtr_tune}")

Best Parameters: {'max_depth': 3, 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 5}
Best Mean Squared Error: 3.605880741282562
Best R-squared: 0.7212047134079859

# The decision tree regressor model performs better with tuned parameters.

After analysing just only the NBA Draft data, using many models, we have noticed that random XGBoost model without hypertuning parameters perfomed better than any models. As it has performed better than any model to predict BPM based on Draft data, we will find the feature importance to understand whcih features of the draft data played important role in predicting BMP.¶

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
# Define feature names and their importance values
features_nba_xgb = [
    'TOTG', 'TOTMP', 'TOTPTS', 'TRB', 'TOTAST', 'FG%', '3P%', 'FT%', 
    'MPPG', 'PTSPG', 'TRBPG', 'ASTPG'
]
importances_nba_xgb = [
    0.2028, 0.0475, 0.1815, 0.0956, 0.0911, 0.1099, 0.0256, 0.0218, 
    0.0427, 0.1349, 0.0221, 0.0245
]

# Create a DataFrame for easy plotting
df_importances_nba_xgb = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': features_nba_xgb,
    'Importance': importances_nba_xgb
})

# Sort the DataFrame by importance
df_importances_nba_xgb = df_importances_nba_xgb.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

# Plot the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(df_importances_nba_xgb['Feature'], df_importances_nba_xgb['Importance'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Importance')
plt.title('Feature Importance of NBA Draft Data (XGBoost Regressor Model)')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert y-axis to have the highest importance at the top
plt.show()

Considering the above outcomes, we can see that the features are not normally distributed. We don't use any kind of transformation techniques to reduce the skewness of the features. This is because the models we use for our analysis are not sensitive to skewded or non-distributed data sets.¶

In [2596]:
# Initialize the XGBoost regressor
xgb_model_nba_combine = xgb.XGBRegressor(
    n_estimators=100,  # Number of boosting rounds (trees)
    learning_rate=0.1, # Shrinkage rate
    max_depth=3,       # Maximum depth of trees
    subsample=0.8,     # Fraction of samples used for fitting individual base learners
    random_state=42
)

In [2601]:
# Hyperparameter Tuning

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'subsample': [0.8, 1.0]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV with XGBRegressor
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=xgb.XGBRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='r2')

# Fit the grid search to the scaled training data
grid_search.fit(X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled, y_NBA_Combine_train)

# Print the best parameters
print(f'Best parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}')

Best parameters: {'learning_rate': 0.2, 'max_depth': 5, 'n_estimators': 300, 'subsample': 0.8}
In [2602]:
# Use the best model for prediction
best_model_xgb_nba_combine = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_best_xgb_nba_combine_tune = best_model_xgb_nba_combine.predict(X_NBA_Combine_test_scaled)
In [2603]:
# Evaluate the best model
mse_best_xgb_nba_combine_tune = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_Combine_test, y_pred_best_xgb_nba_combine_tune)
r2_best_xgb_nba_combine_tune = r2_score(y_NBA_Combine_test, y_pred_best_xgb_nba_combine_tune)

Artificial Neural Network (ANN) for the merged data set "X_NAB_Combine" (NBA Draft data and Draft Combine Metrics)¶

In [2606]:
# Names of split data set = X_NBA_Combine_train, X_NBA_Combine_test, y_NBA_Combine_train, y_NBA_Combine_test
In [2607]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2608]:
# Feature Scaling

scaler = StandardScaler()

# Scale the training data
X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_NBA_Combine_train)

# Scale the test data
X_NBA_Combine_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_NBA_Combine_test)
In [2609]:
# Initialize the model
model_nba_combine_ann = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_nba_combine_ann.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_nba_combine_ann.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_nba_combine_ann.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_nba_combine_ann.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_nba_combine_ann.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2610]:
# Train the model
history = model_nba_combine_ann.fit(X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled, y_NBA_Combine_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

# We now use L2 Regularization to check whether the model with L2 Regularization performs better or not. 

from keras.regularizers import l2

# Define the neural network architecture with L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_ann_l2 = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.01

# Additional hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_ann_l2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
model_nba_combine_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))

# Output layer with 1 neuron (for regression)
model_nba_combine_ann_l2.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model
model_nba_combine_ann_l2.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])

Deep Neural Network (DNN) for the merged data set "X_NAB_Combine" (NBA Draft data and Draft Combine Metrics)¶

In [2620]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2621]:
# Feature Scaling

scaler = StandardScaler()

# Scale the training data
X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_NBA_Combine_train)

# Scale the test data
X_NBA_Combine_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_NBA_Combine_test)
In [2622]:
# Initialize the model
model_nba_combine_dnn = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_nba_combine_dnn.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_nba_combine_dnn.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_nba_combine_dnn.add(Dropout(0.3))  # Dropout layer to prevent overfitting
model_nba_combine_dnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_nba_combine_dnn.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_nba_combine_dnn.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2623]:
# Train the model
history_dnn = model_nba_combine_dnn.fit(X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled, y_NBA_Combine_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

# We can try to reduce overfitting using L2 Regularization

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models, regularizers

# Define the model architecture with L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2 = models.Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.001

# Hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))

# Output layer for regression (for predicting BPM)
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(1))  # Single output for regression

# Compile the model
model_nba_combine_dnn_l2.compile(optimizer='adam', 
              loss='mean_squared_error',  # For regression
              metrics=['mae'])  # Mean Absolute Error as an additional metric

In [2637]:
# Hyperparameter Tuning
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 10, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

# Fit the grid search
grid_search.fit(X_NBA_Combine_train_scaled, y_NBA_Combine_train)

# Best parameters
print(f"Best Parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}")

# Use the best model
best_model_nba_combine_dtr_tune = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predict using the best model
y_pred_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune = best_model_nba_combine_dtr_tune.predict(X_NBA_Combine_test_scaled)

# Evaluate the best model
mse_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune = mean_squared_error(y_NBA_Combine_test, y_pred_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune)
r2_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune = r2_score(y_NBA_Combine_test, y_pred_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune)

print(f"Best Mean Squared Error: {mse_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune}")
print(f"Best R-squared: {r2_best_nba_combine_dtr_tune}")

Best Parameters: {'max_depth': 3, 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 5}
Best Mean Squared Error: 3.605880741282562
Best R-squared: 0.7212047134079859

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
# rf stands for "random forest"
# Define feature names and their importance values
features_nba_combine_rf = [
    'TOTG', 'TOTMP', 'TOTPTS', 'TRB', 'TOTAST', 'FG%', '3P%', 'FT%', 
    'MPPG', 'PTSPG', 'TRBPG', 'ASTPG', 'Standing Reach_Inches', 
    'Height Without Shoes_Inches', 'Wingspan_Inches', 
    'Standing Vertical Leap_Inches', 'Max Vertical Leap_Inches', 
    'Shuttle Run_Secs', 'Lane Agility_Secs', 'Three Quarter Sprint_Secs' 
]
importances_nba_combine_rf = [
   0.1873, 0.0599, 0.1464, 0.0675, 0.0633, 0.2209, 0.0109, 0.0143, 
   0.0375, 0.1065, 0.0095, 0.0104, 0.0068, 0.0035, 0.0042, 0.0149, 
   0.0078, 0.0075, 0.0096, 0.0113
]

# Create a DataFrame for easy plotting
df_importances_nba_combine_rf = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': features_nba_combine_rf,
    'Importance': importances_nba_combine_rf
})

# Sort the DataFrame by importance
df_importances_nba_combine_rf = df_importances_nba_combine_rf.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

# Plot the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(df_importances_nba_combine_rf['Feature'], df_importances_nba_combine_rf['Importance'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Importance')
plt.title('Feature Importance of NBA_Combine Merged Data Set (Random Forest Regressor)')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert y-axis to have the highest importance at the top
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
In [2716]:

X_college_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_college_train)

# Scale the test data
X_college_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_college_test)
In [2717]:
# Initialize the XGBoost regressor
xgb_model_college = xgb.XGBRegressor(
    n_estimators=100,  # Number of boosting rounds (trees)
    learning_rate=0.1, # Shrinkage rate
    max_depth=3,       # Maximum depth of trees
    subsample=0.8,     # Fraction of samples used for fitting individual base learners
    random_state=42
)

# Hyperparameter Tuning

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'subsample': [0.8, 1.0]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV with XGBRegressor
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=xgb.XGBRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='r2')

# Fit the grid search to the scaled training data
grid_search.fit(X_college_train_scaled, y_college_train)

# Print the best parameters
print(f'Best parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}')

Best parameters: {'learning_rate': 0.01, 'max_depth': 7, 'n_estimators': 100, 'subsample': 0.8}
In [2723]:
# Use the best model for prediction
best_model_xgb_college = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_best_xgb_college = best_model_xgb_college.predict(X_college_test_scaled)
In [2724]:
# Evaluate the best model
mse_best_xbg_college_tune = mean_squared_error(y_college_test, y_pred_best_xgb_college)
r2_best_xgb_college_tune = r2_score(y_college_test, y_pred_best_xgb_college)

print(f'Best Mean Squared Error: {mse_best_xbg_college_tune}')
print(f'Best R-squared: {r2_best_xgb_college_tune}')

Artificial Neural Network (ANN) for college stats data¶

In [2726]:
# Names of the split data set = X_college_train, X_college_test, y_college_train, y_college_test
In [2727]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2728]:
# Feature Scaling

scaler = StandardScaler()

# Scale the training data
X_college_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_college_train)

# Scale the test data
X_college_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_college_test)
In [2729]:
# Initialize the model
model_college_ann = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_college_ann.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_college_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_college_ann.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_college_ann.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_college_ann.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_college_ann.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2730]:
# Train the model
history_college = model_college_ann.fit(X_college_train_scaled, y_college_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

In [2734]:
# L2 Regularization to reduce over fitting 

from keras.regularizers import l2

# Define the neural network architecture with L2 regularization
model_college_ann_l2 = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_college_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_college_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.01

# Additional hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_college_ann_l2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
model_college_ann_l2.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))

# Output layer with 1 neuron (for regression)
model_college_ann_l2.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model
model_college_ann_l2.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])

print(f'R-squared: {r2_college_ann_l2}')

Deep Neural Network (DNN) for college stats¶

In [2739]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
In [2740]:
# Feature Scaling

scaler = StandardScaler()

# Scale the training data
X_college_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_college_train)

# Scale the test data
X_college_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_college_test)
In [2741]:
# Initialize the model
model_college_dnn = Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation
model_college_dnn.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_college_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu'))

# Additional hidden layers
model_college_dnn.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_college_dnn.add(Dropout(0.3))  # Dropout layer to prevent overfitting
model_college_dnn.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

# Output layer with a single neuron (since this is a regression problem)
model_college_dnn.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

# Compile the model with mean squared error loss and the Adam optimizer
model_college_dnn.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
In [2742]:
# Train the model
history_college = model_college_dnn.fit(X_college_train_scaled, y_college_train, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

# L2 Regularization

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models, regularizers

# Define the model architecture with L2 regularization
model_college_dnn_l2 = models.Sequential()

# Input layer and first hidden layer with 64 neurons, ReLU activation, and L2 regularization
model_college_dnn_l2.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_college_train_scaled.shape[1], activation='relu',
                kernel_regularizer=l2(0.001)))  # L2 regularization with factor 0.001

# Hidden layers with L2 regularization
model_college_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_college_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
model_college_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))

# Output layer for regression (for predicting BPM)
model_college_dnn_l2.add(layers.Dense(1))  # Single output for regression

# Compile the model
model_college_dnn_l2.compile(optimizer='adam', 
              loss='mean_squared_error',  # For regression
              metrics=['mae'])  # Mean Absolute Error as an additional metric

# Hyperparameter Tuning
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 10, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

# Fit the grid search
grid_search.fit(X_college_train_scaled, y_college_train)

# Best parameters
print(f"Best Parameters: {grid_search.best_params_}")

# Use the best model
best_model_college_dtr_tune = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Predict using the best model
y_pred_best_college_dtr_tune = best_model_college_dtr_tune.predict(X_college_test_scaled)

# Evaluate the best model
mse_best_college_dtr_tune = mean_squared_error(y_college_test, y_pred_best_college_dtr_tune)
r2_best_college_dtr_tune = r2_score(y_college_test, y_pred_best_college_dtr_tune)

print(f"Best Mean Squared Error: {mse_best_college_dtr_tune}")
print(f"Best R-squared: {r2_best_college_dtr_tune}")

Best Parameters: {'max_depth': 3, 'min_samples_leaf': 2, 'min_samples_split': 2}
Best Mean Squared Error: 13.259010986992665
Best R-squared: -0.025144765805669156
